Thanks to the comment from @XtremeBaumer I got a nice solution:
```
// in shared project
@Bean
@ConditionalOnMissingBean(Provider.class)
public class ProviderImpl implements Provider
{
...
}
```

This basically results in the opposite of `@Primary`.

Since the comment has a length limit, let me put it here, Re: @Mathias &quot;if there were two beans with the same @ConditionalOnMissingBean annotations...&quot;

Spring doesn&#39;t provide dedicated bean overriding mechanism, but does support rich bean-selection approches on injection side. One of them is ObjectProvider. Suppose you have 3 beans for your Provider interface:
    
    @Bean
    @Order(10000)
    @ConditionalOnMissingBean
    public Provider enterpriseProvider() {
        return new EnterpiseWideProvider();
    }

    @Bean
    @Order(5000)
    @ConditionalOnMissingBean
    public Provider productLineProvider() {
        return new ProductLineProvider();
    }

    @Bean
    @Order(1000)
    public Provider productProvider() {
        return new MyProductProvider();
    }


Now use ObjectProvider&amp;lt;Provider&amp;gt; instead of Provider on injection side (constructor injection, ObjectProvider&amp;lt;Provider&amp;gt; as a parameter):

    this.provider = objectProvider.orderedStream().findFirst(); // &#39;productProvider&#39;

